title> Beijing Evening News</span><hr size=1> Sorry, this was just too funny not to share. It was in today's LA Times, though you can probably find the story online.<br><br>The jist of it is that last week they published a story that the U.S. Congress had threated to move out of Washington...unless a fancy new capitol was built.<br><br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;Don't get us wrong. We actually love the dilapidated [old] building,&quot; House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert (R.-Ill.) was quoted as saying. &quot;But the cruel reality is, it's no longer suitable for use by a world-class legislature. Its contures are ugly, there's no room to maneuever, there aren't enough bathrooms, and let's not even talk about the parking.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>The article further stated if a new building wasn't erected, the lawmakers were prepared to pack up and move to Memphis, Tenn. or Charlotte, N.C.<br><br>One slight problem though. While the story provided no source...other than a minor reworking of the opening paragraphs it was lifted directly from one of America's leading news sources....The Onion. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Apparently a writer for the Beijing Evening News picked up the item on the internet, changed a bit of the opening paragraphs, and submitted it to his editors, who then published it Monday as a news story, without citing a source.<br><br>Nobody, perhaps even the reporter who submitted it realized that it was a joke.<br><br>Yu Bin the editor in charge of international news acknowledged that he didn't know the source, and that he would tell the reporter to be more careful next time. <br><br>However he adamently ruled out a correction and got very pissy when pressed to comment about the article's complete lack of basis in truth.<br><br>He said in a phone interview, &quot;How do you know whether or not we checked the source before we published the story?&quot; How can you prove it's not correct? Is it incorrect just because YOU say it is?&quot;<br><br>The Onion parody featured an architect's rendering of a proposed futuristic Capitol, complete with a retractable dome, a &quot;DAncing Waters fountain&quot; and &quot;55 more luxury boxes than the current building&quot;.<br><br>The Beijing paper even reproduced the entire illustration without crediting The Onion. There wasn't even a caption explaining what the drawing was. <br><br>Robert Siegal, editor in chief of the Onion had some comments though. He stated he was amazed at the Chinese paper's gullibility and commented, that the Beijing Paper's 'cribbing' of the article was not suprising in a land where movies, pop albums and books are pirated and sold on the streets.<br><br>Though still controlled by the government, the media in China has become more free-wheeling, and more competitive, forced to duke it out for a market share and turn a profit. Most papers are now relying on freelancers to provide all sorts of content. This has given a rise to a slew of young, Internet savvy, English speaking writers who freely lift stuff from the Web and submit it to editors who have adopted a 'don't ask, don't tell' policy towards the material's origins.<br><br>Anyway, the article I'm taking this all from was written by Henry Chu, Times Staff Writer. Any mistakes, are of course mine. <br><br>I just thought it was really funny. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br><br>Now for a minute of social commentary to justify my placing it here. It's not just Beijing that's gone through this, Russia has as well. And with a 'free press' comes responsibility. The United States went through a period of yellow journalism, and fortunately (well in most ways) the fourth estate has evolved to a point where integrity is key for a media outlet to maintain themselves. While the Chinese press is hardly &quot;free&quot; yet, they're also still evolving, attempting to compete for business while under government control. <br><br>The dangers of course is in trusting a media outlet as your sole source of information. Even in the middle east, a doctor wrote an article, which appeared in a promenant Arabic newspaper claiming that Jews use the blood of Christian children (and non-Jewish children) in the baking of bread during their rituals. It's an old ugly myth that has perpetuated itself for hundreds of years, used in ugly smear campaigns against Jews. Yet, I wonder how many people who read that article, written by a doctor <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> believed it</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br><br>The same is true, fortunately on a lesser scale, with our newspapers. Journalists have falsified stories before, or in most cases of error, simply made an honest mistake. However, it shows that while getting information from other sources is necessary..since we hardly have the time to research all the information ourselves...knowing the source, and having a dose of skepticism is also a good idea as well. Thinking for yourself is even better. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><a href="http://marian333.livejournal.com" target="_blank"><img src="http://eqscreenshot.homestead.com/files/eq_sig_tarot.jpg" border="0"></a> <br><font style='font-size=10px'>And I looked, and behold a pale horse: and her name that sat on him was Tarot, and Hell followed with her. </FONT><p><A HREF="mailto:Marian333@hotmail.com?Subject=Lanys Board">Bitch At Tarot!</A> </p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/uhsianlichen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hsian L